SSH Keys – Concepts and Essential Commands

1. Introduction

SSH (Secure Shell) is a cryptographic network protocol used to securely access remote systems
and services. SSH keys are widely used for authentication with Git platforms and remote servers.


2. What Is an SSH Key?

An SSH key pair consists of a Private Key (kept secret) and a Public Key (shared with servers).
Authentication succeeds when the server verifies that you own the matching private key.


3. Why Use SSH Keys?

• Stronger security than passwords
• No repeated credential entry
• Required for automation and CI/CD
• Recommended for Git operations


4. Generating an SSH Key

Recommended command:
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"
Alternative (RSA 4096):
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your_email@example.com"


5. Starting SSH Agent

Linux/macOS:
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
Windows (Git Bash):
eval $(ssh-agent -s)


6. Adding Private Key to Agent

ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
Verify:
ssh-add -l


7. Testing SSH Connection

Example for GitHub:
ssh -T git@github.com


8. Clone Using SSH

git clone git@github.com:username/project.git


9. Security Best Practices

• Never share your private key
• Use strong passphrase
• Set proper permissions:
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
chmod 644 ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pup